# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ito-stratonovich
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ito-stratonovich/doob-meyer-decomposition-theorem] The **Doob–Meyer decomposition theorem** is a theorem in stochastic calculus stating the conditions under which a submartingale may be decomposed in a unique way as the sum of a martingale and an increasing predictable process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/doob-meyer-decomposition-theorem] In 1953, Doob published the Doob decomposition theorem which gives a unique decomposition for certain discrete time martingales.
[src:ito-stratonovich/doob-meyer-decomposition-theorem] He conjectured a continuous time version of the theorem and in two publications in 1962 and 1963 Paul-André Meyer proved such a theorem, which became known as the Doob-Meyer decomposition.
[src:ito-stratonovich/doob-meyer-decomposition-theorem] In honor of Doob, Meyer used the term "class D" to refer to the class of supermartingales for which his unique decomposition theorem applied.
[src:ito-stratonovich/doob-meyer-decomposition-theorem] Let $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {F}},({\mathcal {F}}_{t})_{t\geq 0},\mathbb {P} )$ be a filtered probability space satisfying the usual conditions (i.e. the filtration is right-continuous and complete; see Filtration (probability theory)).
[src:ito-stratonovich/doob-meyer-decomposition-theorem] The decomposition $(M,A)$ is unique up to indistinguishability.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The central concept is the Itô stochastic integral, a stochastic generalization of the Riemann–Stieltjes integral in analysis.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The integrands and the integrators are now stochastic processes: $Y_{t}=\int _{0}^{t}H_{s}\,dX_{s},$ where *H* is a locally square-integrable process adapted to the filtration generated by *X* (Revuz & Yor 1999, Chapter IV), which is a Brownian motion or, more generally, a semimartingale.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The result of the integration is then another stochastic process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Concretely, the integral from 0 to any particular t is a random variable, defined as a limit of a certain sequence of random variables.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The paths of Brownian motion fail to satisfy the requirements to be able to apply the standard techniques of calculus.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] So with the integrand a stochastic process, the Itô stochastic integral amounts to an integral with respect to a function which is not differentiable at any point and has infinite variation over every time interval.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The main insight is that the integral can be defined as long as the integrand *H* is adapted, which loosely speaking means that its value at time t can only depend on information available up until this time.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Roughly speaking, one chooses a sequence of partitions of the interval from 0 to t and constructs Riemann sums.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Every time we are computing a Riemann sum, we are using a particular instantiation of the integrator.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] It is crucial which point in each of the small intervals is used to compute the value of the function.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The limit then is taken in probability as the mesh of the partition is going to zero.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Numerous technical details have to be taken care of to show that this limit exists and is independent of the particular sequence of partitions.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Typically, the left end of the interval is used.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Important results of Itô calculus include the integration by parts formula and Itô's lemma, which is a change of variables formula.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] These differ from the formulas of standard calculus, due to quadratic variation terms.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] This can be contrasted to the Stratonovich integral as an alternative formulation; it does follow the chain rule, and does not require Itô's lemma.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The two integral forms can be converted to one-another.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The Stratonovich integral is obtained as the limiting form of a Riemann sum that employs the average of stochastic variable over each small timestep, whereas the Itô integral considers it only at the beginning.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] In mathematical finance, the described evaluation strategy of the integral is conceptualized as that we are first deciding what to do, then observing the change in the prices.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The integrand is how much stock we hold, the integrator represents the movement of the prices, and the integral is how much money we have in total including what our stock is worth, at any given moment.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The prices of stocks and other traded financial assets can be modeled by stochastic processes such as Brownian motion or, more often, geometric Brownian motion (see Black–Scholes).
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Then, the Itô stochastic integral represents the payoff of a continuous-time trading strategy consisting of holding an amount *Ht* of the stock at time *t*.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] In this situation, the condition that *H* is adapted corresponds to the necessary restriction that the trading strategy can only make use of the available information at any time.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] This prevents the possibility of unlimited gains through clairvoyance: buying the stock just before each uptick in the market and selling before each downtick.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Similarly, the condition that *H* is adapted implies that the stochastic integral will not diverge when calculated as a limit of Riemann sums (Revuz & Yor 1999, Chapter IV).
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The process *Y* defined before as $Y_{t}=\int _{0}^{t}H\,dX\equiv \int _{0}^{t}H_{s}\,dX_{s},$ is itself a stochastic process with time parameter *t*, which is also sometimes written as *Y* = *H* · *X* (Rogers & Williams 2000).
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Alternatively, the integral is often written in differential form *dY* = *H* *dX*, which is equivalent to *Y* − *Y*0 = *H* · *X*.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] A Brownian motion *B* is understood to be an ${\mathcal {F}}_{t}$ -Brownian motion, which is just a standard Brownian motion with the properties that *B**t* is ${\mathcal {F}}_{t}$ -measurable and that *B**t*+*s* − *B**t* is independent of ${\mathcal {F}}_{t}$ for all *s*,*t* ≥ 0 (Revuz & Yor 1999).
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The Itô integral can be defined in a manner similar to the Riemann–Stieltjes integral, that is as a limit in probability of Riemann sums; such a limit does not necessarily exist pathwise.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Suppose that *B* is a Wiener process (Brownian motion) and that *H* is a right-continuous (càdlàg), adapted and locally bounded process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] It can be shown that this limit converges in probability.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] For some applications, such as martingale representation theorems and local times, the integral is needed for processes that are not continuous.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The predictable processes form the smallest class that is closed under taking limits of sequences and contains all adapted left-continuous processes.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] If *H* is any predictable process such that ∫0*t* *H*2 *ds* < ∞ for every *t* ≥ 0 then the integral of *H* with respect to *B* can be defined, and *H* is said to be *B*-integrable.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Any such process can be approximated by a sequence *Hn* of left-continuous, adapted and locally bounded processes, in the sense that $\int _{0}^{t}(H-H_{n})^{2}\,ds\to 0$ in probability.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Then, the Itô integral is $\int _{0}^{t}H\,dB=\lim _{n\to \infty }\int _{0}^{t}H_{n}\,dB$ where, again, the limit can be shown to converge in probability.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The stochastic integral satisfies the Itô isometry $\mathbb {E} \left[\left(\int _{0}^{t}H_{s}\,dB_{s}\right)^{2}\right]=\mathbb {E} \left[\int _{0}^{t}H_{s}^{2}\,ds\right]$ which holds when *H* is bounded or, more generally, when the integral on the right hand side is finite.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Here, *B* is a Brownian motion and it is required that σ is a predictable *B*-integrable process, and μ is predictable and (Lebesgue) integrable.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] This is defined for all locally bounded and predictable integrands.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] More generally, it is required that *Hσ* be *B*-integrable and *Hμ* be Lebesgue integrable, so that $\int _{0}^{t}\left(H^{2}\sigma ^{2}+|H\mu |\right)ds<\infty .$ Such predictable processes *H* are called *X*-integrable.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] An important result for the study of Itô processes is Itô's lemma.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] This is the stochastic calculus version of the change of variables formula and chain rule.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] It differs from the standard result due to the additional term involving the second derivative of *f*, which comes from the property that Brownian motion has non-zero quadratic variation.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The Itô integral is defined with respect to a semimartingale *X*.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] These are processes which can be decomposed as *X* = *M* + *A* for a local martingale *M* and finite variation process *A*.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Important examples of such processes include Brownian motion, which is a martingale, and Lévy processes.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] For a left continuous, locally bounded and adapted process *H* the integral *H* · *X* exists, and can be calculated as a limit of Riemann sums.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The stochastic integral of left-continuous processes is general enough for studying much of stochastic calculus.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] For example, it is sufficient for applications of Itô's Lemma, changes of measure via Girsanov's theorem, and for the study of stochastic differential equations.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] However, it is inadequate for other important topics such as martingale representation theorems and local times.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The integral extends to all predictable and locally bounded integrands, in a unique way, such that the dominated convergence theorem holds.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The uniqueness of the extension from left-continuous to predictable integrands is a result of the monotone class lemma.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] In general, the stochastic integral *H* · *X* can be defined even in cases where the predictable process *H* is not locally bounded.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Associativity of stochastic integration implies that *H* is *X*-integrable, with integral *H* · *X* = *Y*, if and only if *Y*0 = 0 and *K* · *Y* = (*KH*) · *X*.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The set of *X*-integrable processes is denoted by *L*(*X*).
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] As with ordinary calculus, integration by parts is an important result in stochastic calculus.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The integration by parts formula for the Itô integral differs from the standard result due to the inclusion of a quadratic covariation term.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] This term comes from the fact that Itô calculus deals with processes with non-zero quadratic variation, which only occurs for infinite variation processes (such as Brownian motion).
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The result is similar to the integration by parts theorem for the Riemann–Stieltjes integral but has an additional quadratic variation term.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Itô's lemma is the version of the chain rule or change of variables formula which applies to the Itô integral.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] It is one of the most powerful and frequently used theorems in stochastic calculus.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The formula can be generalized to include an explicit time-dependence in $f,$ and in other ways (see Itô's lemma).
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] An important property of the Itô integral is that it preserves the local martingale property.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] If *M* is a local martingale and *H* is a locally bounded predictable process then *H* · *M* is also a local martingale.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] For integrands which are not locally bounded, there are examples where *H* · *M* is not a local martingale.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] However, this can only occur when *M* is not continuous.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] If *M* is a continuous local martingale then a predictable process *H* is *M*-integrable if and only if $\int _{0}^{t}H^{2}\,d[M]<\infty ,$ for each t, and *H* · *M* is always a local martingale.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The most general statement for a discontinuous local martingale *M* is that if (*H*2 · [*M*])1/2 is locally integrable then *H* · *M* exists and is a local martingale.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] For bounded integrands, the Itô stochastic integral preserves the space of *square integrable* martingales, which is the set of càdlàg martingales *M* such that E[*M**t*2] is finite for all t.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The Itô isometry is often used as an important step in the construction of the stochastic integral, by defining *H* · *M* to be the unique extension of this isometry from a certain class of simple integrands to all bounded and predictable processes.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] For any *p* > 1, and bounded predictable integrand, the stochastic integral preserves the space of *p*-integrable martingales.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] These are càdlàg martingales such that E(|*Mt*|*p*) is finite for all t.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] However, this is not always true in the case where *p* = 1.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] There are examples of integrals of bounded predictable processes with respect to martingales which are not themselves martingales.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The maximum process of a càdlàg process *M* is written as *M*t* = sup*s* ≤*t* |*Ms*|.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] For any *p* ≥ 1 and bounded predictable integrand, the stochastic integral preserves the space of càdlàg martingales *M* such that E[(*M*t*)*p*] is finite for all t.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] If *p* > 1 then this is the same as the space of *p*-integrable martingales, by Doob's inequalities.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] These are used to show that if (*M*t*)*p* is integrable and *H* is a bounded predictable process then $\mathbb {E} \left[((H\cdot M)_{t}^{*})^{p}\right]\leq C\mathbb {E} \left[(H^{2}\cdot [M]_{t})^{\frac {p}{2}}\right]<\infty$ and, consequently, *H* · *M* is a *p*-integrable martingale.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] More generally, this statement is true whenever (*H*2 · [*M*])*p*/2 is integrable.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Proofs that the Itô integral is well defined typically proceed by first looking at very simple integrands, such as piecewise constant, left continuous and adapted processes where the integral can be written explicitly.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] It can then be extended to all *B*-integrable processes by localization.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] This method allows the integral to be defined with respect to any Itô process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] For a general semimartingale *X*, the decomposition *X* = *M* + *A* into a local martingale *M* plus a finite variation process *A* can be used.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Then, the integral can be shown to exist separately with respect to *M* and *A* and combined using linearity, *H* · *X* = *H* · *M* + *H* · *A*, to get the integral with respect to *X*.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The standard Lebesgue–Stieltjes integral allows integration to be defined with respect to finite variation processes, so the existence of the Itô integral for semimartingales will follow from any construction for local martingales.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] For a càdlàg square integrable martingale *M*, a generalized form of the Itô isometry can be used.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] First, the Doob–Meyer decomposition theorem is used to show that a decomposition *M*2 = *N* + ⟨*M*⟩ exists, where *N* is a martingale and ⟨*M*⟩ is a right-continuous, increasing and predictable process starting at zero.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] This uniquely defines ⟨*M*⟩, which is referred to as the *predictable quadratic variation* of *M*.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The Itô isometry for square integrable martingales is then $\mathbb {E} \left[(H\cdot M_{t})^{2}\right]=\mathbb {E} \left[\int _{0}^{t}H_{s}^{2}\,d\langle M\rangle _{s}\right],$ which can be proved directly for simple predictable integrands.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] As with the case above for Brownian motion, a continuous linear extension can be used to uniquely extend to all predictable integrands satisfying *E*[*H*2 · ⟨*M*⟩*t*] < ∞.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] This method can be extended to all local square integrable martingales by localization.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Finally, the Doob–Meyer decomposition can be used to decompose any local martingale into the sum of a local square integrable martingale and a finite variation process, allowing the Itô integral to be constructed with respect to any semimartingale.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The latter applies directly to local martingales without having to first deal with the square integrable martingale case.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Alternative proofs exist only making use of the fact that *X* is càdlàg, adapted, and the set {*H* · *Xt*: |*H*| ≤ 1 is simple previsible} is bounded in probability for each time *t*, which is an alternative definition for *X* to be a semimartingale.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] A continuous linear extension can be used to construct the integral for all left-continuous and adapted integrands with right limits everywhere (caglad or L-processes).
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] This is general enough to be able to apply techniques such as Itô's lemma (Protter 2004).
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Also, a Khintchine inequality can be used to prove the dominated convergence theorem and extend the integral to general predictable integrands (Bichteler 2002).
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] The Itô calculus is first and foremost defined as an integral calculus as outlined above.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Malliavin calculus provides a theory of differentiation for random variables defined over Wiener space, including an integration by parts formula (Nualart 2006).
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] This representation theorem can be interpreted formally as saying that α is the "time derivative" of *M* with respect to Brownian motion *B*, since α is precisely the process that must be integrated up to time t to obtain *M**t* − *M*0, as in deterministic calculus.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] In physics, usually stochastic differential equations (SDEs), such as Langevin equations, are used, rather than stochastic integrals.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] Here an Itô stochastic differential equation (SDE) is often formulated via ${\dot {x}}_{k}=h_{k}+g_{kl}\xi _{l},$ where $\xi _{j}$ is Gaussian white noise with $\langle \xi _{k}(t_{1})\,\xi _{l}(t_{2})\rangle =\delta _{kl}\delta (t_{1}-t_{2})$ and Einstein's summation convention is used.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] SDEs frequently occur in physics in Stratonovich form, as limits of stochastic differential equations driven by colored noise if the correlation time of the noise term approaches zero.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-calculus] For a recent treatment of different interpretations of stochastic differential equations see for example (Lau & Lubensky 2007).
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] In mathematics, **Itô's lemma** or **Itô's formula** (also called the **Itô–Doeblin formula**) is an identity used in Itô calculus to find the differential of a time-dependent function of a stochastic process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] It serves as the stochastic calculus counterpart of the chain rule.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] It can be heuristically derived by forming the Taylor series expansion of the function up to its second derivatives and retaining terms up to first order in the time increment and second order in the Wiener process increment.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] The lemma is widely employed in mathematical finance, and its best known application is in the derivation of the Black–Scholes equation for option values.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] This result was discovered by Japanese mathematician Kiyoshi Itô in 1951.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] Suppose we are given the stochastic differential equation $dX_{t}=\mu _{t}\ dt+\sigma _{t}\ dB_{t},$ where *B**t* is a Wiener process and the functions $\mu _{t},\sigma _{t}$ are deterministic (not stochastic) functions of time.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] This expression lets us easily read off the mean and variance of $X_{t}$ (which has no higher moments).
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] However, sometimes we are faced with a stochastic differential equation for a more complex process $Y_{t},$ in which the process appears on both sides of the differential equation.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] That is, say $dY_{t}=a_{1}(Y_{t},t)\ dt+a_{2}(Y_{t},t)\ dB_{t},$ for some functions $a_{1}$ and $a_{2}.$ In this case, we cannot immediately write a formal solution as we did for the simpler case above.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] Instead, we hope to write the process $Y_{t}$ as a function of a simpler process $X_{t}$ taking the form above.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] That is, we want to identify three functions $f(t,x),\mu _{t},$ and $\sigma _{t},$ such that $Y_{t}=f(t,X_{t})$ and $dX_{t}=\mu _{t}\ dt+\sigma _{t}\ dB_{t}.$ In practice, Ito's lemma is used in order to find this transformation.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] Finally, once we have transformed the problem into the simpler type of problem, we can determine the mean and higher moments of the process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] We derive Itô's lemma by expanding a Taylor series and applying the rules of stochastic calculus.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] Suppose we know that $X_{t},X_{t+dt}$ are two jointly-Gaussian distributed random variables, and f is nonlinear but has a continuous second derivative, then in general, neither of $f(X_{t}),f(X_{t+dt})$ is Gaussian, and their joint distribution is also not Gaussian.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] However, since $X_{t+dt}\mid X_{t}$ is Gaussian, we might still find $f(X_{t+dt})\mid f(X_{t})$ is Gaussian.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] This is not true when $dt$ is finite, but when $dt$ becomes infinitesimal, this becomes true.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] The key idea is that $X_{t+dt}=X_{t}+\mu _{t}\,dt+dW_{t}$ has a deterministic part and a noisy part.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] When f is nonlinear, the noisy part has a deterministic contribution.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] If f is convex, then the deterministic contribution is positive (by Jensen's inequality).
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] The random part is non-Gaussian, but the non-Gaussian parts decay faster than the Gaussian part, and at the $dt\to 0$ limit, only the Gaussian part remains.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] To understand why there should be a contribution due to convexity, consider the simplest case of geometric Brownian walk (of the stock market): $S_{t+dt}=S_{t}(1+dB_{t})$ .
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] However, although the expectation of $X_{t}$ remains constant, the expectation of $S_{t}$ grows.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] Intuitively it is because the downside is limited at zero, but the upside is unlimited.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] That is, while $X_{t}$ is normally distributed, $S_{t}$ is log-normally distributed.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] In the following subsections we discuss versions of Itô's lemma for different types of stochastic processes.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] This immediately implies that *f*(*t*,*X**t*) is itself an Itô drift-diffusion process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] where $\nabla _{\mathbf {X} }f$ is the gradient of *f* w.r.t.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] We may also define functions on discontinuous stochastic processes.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] The Poisson process model for jumps is that the probability of one jump in the interval [*t*, *t* + Δ*t*] is *h*Δ*t* plus higher order terms. h could be a constant, a deterministic function of time, or a stochastic process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] The survival probability *ps*(*t*) is the probability that no jump has occurred in the interval [0, *t*].
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] Let *S*(*t*) be a discontinuous stochastic process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] Write $S(t^{-})$ for the value of *S* as we approach *t* from the left.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] Write $d_{j}S(t)$ for the non-infinitesimal change in *S*(*t*) as a result of a jump.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] Let *z* be the magnitude of the jump and let $\eta (S(t^{-}),z)$ be the distribution of *z*.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] Now, define the *compensated process* $J_{S}(t)$ associated with $S(t)$ , which simply means that we subtract off the mean change in $S(t)$ so that $J_{S}(t)$ is a martingale.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] Consider a function $g(S(t),t)$ of the jump process *dS*(*t*).
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] Itô's lemma for a process which is the sum of a drift-diffusion process and a jump process is just the sum of the Itô's lemma for the individual parts.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] Itô's lemma can also be applied to general d-dimensional semimartingales, which need not be continuous.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] In general, a semimartingale is a càdlàg process, and an additional jump term needs to be added to the Itô's formula.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] For any cadlag process *Yt*, the left limit in t is denoted by *Yt−*, which is a left-continuous process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] The jumps are written as Δ*Yt* = *Yt* − *Yt−*.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] This differs from the formula for continuous semi-martingales by the last term summing over the jumps of *X*, which ensures that the jump of the right hand side at time t is Δ*f*(*Xt*).
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] A process S is said to follow a geometric Brownian motion with constant volatility *σ* and constant drift *μ* if it satisfies the stochastic differential equation $dS_{t}=\sigma S_{t}\,dB_{t}+\mu S_{t}\,dt$ , for a Brownian motion *B*.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] The correction term of − ⁠*σ*2/2⁠ corresponds to the difference between the median and mean of the log-normal distribution, or equivalently for this distribution, the geometric mean and arithmetic mean, with the median (geometric mean) being lower.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] This is due to the AM–GM inequality, and corresponds to the logarithm being concave (or convex upwards), so the correction term can accordingly be interpreted as a convexity correction.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] This is an infinitesimal version of the fact that the annualized return is less than the average return, with the difference proportional to the variance.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] See geometric moments of the log-normal distribution for further discussion.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] The same factor of ⁠*σ*2/2⁠ appears in the *d*1 and *d*2 auxiliary variables of the Black–Scholes formula, and can be interpreted as a consequence of Itô's lemma.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] The Doléans-Dade exponential (or stochastic exponential) of a continuous semimartingale *X* can be defined as the solution to the SDE *dY* = *Y dX* with initial condition *Y*0 = 1.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] Itô's lemma can be used to derive the Black–Scholes equation for an option.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] Suppose a stock price follows a geometric Brownian motion given by the stochastic differential equation *dS* = *S*(*σ* *dB* + *μ* *dt*).
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] The term ⁠∂*f*/∂*S*⁠ *dS* represents the change in value in time *dt* of the trading strategy consisting of holding an amount ⁠∂ *f*/∂*S*⁠ of the stock.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] This strategy replicates the option if *V* = *f*(*t*,*S*).
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] Then we can use the multi-dimensional form of Ito's lemma to find an expression for $d(X_{t}^{1}X_{t}^{2})$ .
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] This is a generalisation of Leibniz's product rule to Ito processes, which are non-differentiable.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] so we see that the product $X_{t}^{1}X_{t}^{2}$ is itself an Itô drift-diffusion process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] Hans Föllmer provided a non-probabilistic proof of the Itô formula and showed that it holds for all functions with finite quadratic variation.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] Let $f\in C^{2}$ be a real-valued function and $x:[0,\infty ]\to \mathbb {R}$ a right-continuous function with left limits and finite quadratic variation $[x]$ .
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] Rama Cont and Nicolas Perkowski extended the Itô formula to functions with finite p-th variation where $p\geq 2$ is an arbitrarily large integer.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] There exist some extensions to infinite-dimensional spaces (e.g.
[src:ito-stratonovich/itô-s-lemma] Pardoux, Gyöngy-Krylov, Brzezniak-van Neerven-Veraar-Weis).
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] In mathematics, **quadratic variation** is used in the analysis of stochastic processes such as Brownian motion and other martingales.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] Quadratic variation is just one kind of variation of a process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] Suppose that $X_{t}$ is a real-valued stochastic process defined on a probability space $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {F}},\mathbb {P} )$ and with time index t ranging over the non-negative real numbers.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] where P ranges over partitions of the interval $[0,t]$ and the norm of the partition P is the mesh.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] This limit, if it exists, is defined using convergence in probability.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] Notation: the quadratic variation is also notated as $\langle X\rangle _{t}$ or $\langle X,X\rangle _{t}$ .
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] A process X is said to have *finite variation* if it has bounded variation over every finite time interval (with probability 1).
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] Such processes are very common including, in particular, all continuously differentiable functions.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] The quadratic variation exists for all continuous finite variation processes, and is zero.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] This statement can be generalized to non-continuous processes.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] Any càdlàg finite variation process X has quadratic variation equal to the sum of the squares of the jumps of X .
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] To state this more precisely, the left limit of $X_{t}$ with respect to t is denoted by $X_{t-}$ , and the jump of X at time t can be written as $\Delta X_{t}=X_{t}-X_{t-}$ .
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] The proof that continuous finite variation processes have zero quadratic variation follows from the following inequality.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] Here, P is a partition of the interval $[0,t]$ , and $V_{t}(X)$ is the variation of X over $[0,t]$ .
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] By the continuity of X , this vanishes in the limit as $\Vert P\Vert$ goes to zero.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] The quadratic variation of a standard Brownian motion B exists, and is given by $[B]_{t}=t$ , however the limit in the definition is meant in the almost surely sense and the $L^{2}$ sense, but not pathwise.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] Quadratic variations and covariations of all semimartingales can be shown to exist.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] They form an important part of the theory of stochastic calculus, appearing in Itô's lemma, which is the generalization of the chain rule to the Itô integral.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] All càdlàg martingales, and local martingales have well defined quadratic variation, which follows from the fact that such processes are examples of semimartingales.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] It can be shown that the quadratic variation $[M]$ of a general locally square integrable martingale M is the unique right-continuous and increasing process starting at zero, with jumps $\Delta [M]=\Delta M^{2}$ and such that $M^{2}-[M]$ is a local martingale.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] A proof of existence of M (without using stochastic calculus) is given in Karandikar–Rao (2014).
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] This result holds whenever M is a càdlàg square integrable martingale and H is a bounded predictable process, and is often used in the construction of the Itô integral.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] Another important result is the **Burkholder–Davis–Gundy inequality**, named for Donald Burkholder, Burgess Davis, and Richard Floyd Gundy.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] This gives bounds for the maximum of a martingale in terms of the quadratic variation.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] Here, $c_{p}<C_{p}$ are constants depending on the choice of p , but not depending on the martingale M or time t used.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] If M is a continuous local martingale, then the Burkholder–Davis–Gundy inequality holds for any $p>0$ .
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] An alternative process, the **predictable quadratic variation** is sometimes used for locally square integrable martingales.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] This is written as $\langle M_{t}\rangle$ , and is defined to be the unique right-continuous and increasing predictable process starting at zero such that $M^{2}-\langle M\rangle$ is a local martingale.
[src:ito-stratonovich/quadratic-variation] Its existence follows from the Doob–Meyer decomposition theorem and, for continuous local martingales, it is the same as the quadratic variation.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] In probability theory, a real-valued stochastic process *X* is called a **semimartingale** if it can be decomposed as the sum of a local martingale and an adapted finite-variation process whose paths are right-continuous with left limits (càdlàg).
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] Semimartingales are "good integrators", forming the largest class of processes with respect to which the Itô integral and the Stratonovich integral can be defined.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] The class of semimartingales is quite large (including, for example, all continuously differentiable processes, Brownian motion and Poisson processes).
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] Submartingales and supermartingales together represent a subset of the semimartingales.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] where *M* is a local martingale and *A* is a càdlàg adapted process of locally bounded variation.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] This means that for almost all $\omega \in \Omega$ and all compact intervals $I\subset [0,\infty )$ , the sample path $I\ni s\mapsto A_{s}(\omega )$ is of bounded variation.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] Because every martingale in a right-continuous filtration has a càdlàg version, one commonly considers semimartingale X to have right-continuous paths with left limits denoted by $X_{-}$ .
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] The jumps of a semimartingale are then given by $\Delta X=X-X_{-}$ .
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] An **R***n*-valued process *X* = (*X*1,...,*X**n*) is a semimartingale if each of its components *X**i* is a semimartingale.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] First, the simple predictable processes are defined to be linear combinations of processes of the form *H**t* = *A*1{*t* > *T*} for stopping times *T* and *F**T* -measurable random variables *A*.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] This is extended to all simple predictable processes by the linearity of *H* ⋅ *X* in *H*.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] The Bichteler–Dellacherie Theorem states that these two definitions are equivalent (Protter 2004, p.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] Although most continuous and adapted processes studied in the literature are semimartingales, this is not always the case.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] By definition, every semimartingale is a sum of a local martingale and a finite-variation process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] However, this decomposition is not unique.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] A continuous semimartingale uniquely decomposes as *X* = *M* + *A* where *M* is a continuous local martingale and *A* is a continuous finite-variation process starting at zero.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] A special semimartingale is a real-valued process *X* with the decomposition $X=M^{X}+B^{X}$ , where $M^{X}$ is a local martingale and $B^{X}$ is a predictable finite-variation process starting at zero.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] If this decomposition exists, then it is unique up to a P-null set.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] Every special semimartingale is a semimartingale.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] Conversely, a semimartingale is a special semimartingale if and only if the process *X*t* ≡ sup*s* ≤ *t* |X*s*| is locally integrable (Protter 2004, p.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] For example, every continuous semimartingale is a special semimartingale, in which case *M* and *A* are both continuous processes.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] Recall that ${\mathcal {E}}(X)$ denotes the stochastic exponential of semimartingale X .
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] By this definition, *time* is a purely discontinuous semimartingale even though it exhibits no jumps at all.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] The alternative (and preferred) terminology *quadratic pure-jump* semimartingale for a purely discontinuous semimartingale (Protter 2004, p.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] 71) is motivated by the fact that the quadratic variation of a purely discontinuous semimartingale is a pure jump process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] Every finite-variation semimartingale is a quadratic pure-jump semimartingale.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] An adapted continuous process is a quadratic pure-jump semimartingale if and only if it is of finite variation.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] For every semimartingale X there is a unique continuous local martingale $X^{c}$ starting at zero such that $X-X^{c}$ is a quadratic pure-jump semimartingale (He, Wang & Yan 1992, p.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] The local martingale $X^{c}$ is called the *continuous martingale part of* *X*.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] Observe that $X^{c}$ is measure-specific.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] If *P* and *Q* are two equivalent measures then $X^{c}(P)$ is typically different from $X^{c}(Q)$ , while both $X-X^{c}(P)$ and $X-X^{c}(Q)$ are quadratic pure-jump semimartingales.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] Typical examples of the "qc" component are Itô process and Lévy process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] The "dp" component is often taken to be a Markov chain but in general the predictable jump times may not be isolated points; for example, in principle $X^{\mathrm {dp} }$ may jump at every rational time.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] Observe also that $X^{\mathrm {dp} }$ is not necessarily of finite variation, even though it is equal to the sum of its jumps (in the semimartingale topology).
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] For example, on the time interval $[0,\infty )$ take $X^{\mathrm {dp} }$ to have independent increments, with jumps at times $\{\tau _{n}=2-1/n\}_{n\in \mathbb {N} }$ taking values $\pm 1/n$ with equal probability.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] The concept of semimartingales, and the associated theory of stochastic calculus, extends to processes taking values in a differentiable manifold.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] A process *X* on the manifold *M* is a semimartingale if *f*(*X*) is a semimartingale for every smooth function *f* from *M* to **R**.
[src:ito-stratonovich/semimartingale] 24) Stochastic calculus for semimartingales on general manifolds requires the use of the Stratonovich integral.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] In stochastic processes, the **Stratonovich integral** or **Fisk–Stratonovich integral** (developed simultaneously by Ruslan Stratonovich and Donald Fisk) is a stochastic integral, the most common alternative to the Itô integral.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] Although the Itô integral is the usual choice in applied mathematics, the Stratonovich integral is frequently used in physics.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] In some circumstances, integrals in the Stratonovich definition are easier to manipulate.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] Unlike the Itô calculus, Stratonovich integrals are defined such that the chain rule of ordinary calculus holds.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] Perhaps the most common situation in which these are encountered is as the solution to Stratonovich stochastic differential equations (SDEs).
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] These are equivalent to Itô SDEs and it is possible to convert between the two whenever one definition is more convenient.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] The Stratonovich integral can be defined in a manner similar to the Riemann integral, that is as a limit of Riemann sums.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] Suppose that $W:[0,T]\times \Omega \to \mathbb {R}$ is a Wiener process and $X:[0,T]\times \Omega \to \mathbb {R}$ is a semimartingale adapted to the natural filtration of the Wiener process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] as the mesh of the partition $0=t_{0}<t_{1}<\dots <t_{k}=T$ of $[0,T]$ tends to 0 (in the style of a Riemann–Stieltjes integral).
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] The circle $\circ$ is a notational device, used to distinguish this integral from the Itô integral.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] This latter rule is akin to the chain rule of ordinary calculus.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] Stochastic integrals can rarely be solved in analytic form, making stochastic numerical integration an important topic in all uses of stochastic integrals.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] Various numerical approximations converge to the Stratonovich integral, and variations of these are used to solve Stratonovich SDEs (Kloeden & Platen 1992).
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] Note however that the most widely used Euler scheme (the Euler–Maruyama method) for the numeric solution of Langevin equations requires the equation to be in Itô form.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] This notation is often used to formulate stochastic differential equations (SDEs), which are really equations about stochastic integrals.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] The Itô integral of the process X with respect to the Wiener process W is denoted by $\int _{0}^{T}X_{t}\,\mathrm {d} W_{t}$ (without the circle).
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] This integral does not obey the ordinary chain rule as the Stratonovich integral does; instead one has to use the slightly more complicated Itô's lemma.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] where f is any continuously differentiable function of two variables W and t and the last integral is an Itô integral (Kloeden & Platen 1992, p.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] Langevin equations exemplify the importance of specifying the interpretation (Stratonovich or Itô) in a given problem.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] Suppose $X_{t}$ is a time-homogeneous Itô diffusion with continuously differentiable diffusion coefficient $\sigma$ , i.e. it satisfies the SDE $\mathrm {d} X_{t}=\mu (X_{t})\,\mathrm {d} t+\sigma (X_{t})\,\mathrm {d} W_{t}$ .
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] Obviously, if $\sigma$ is independent of $X_{t}$ , the two interpretations will lead to the same form for the Langevin equation.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] In that case, the noise term is called "additive" (since the noise term $dW_{t}$ is multiplied by only a fixed coefficient).
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] Otherwise, if $\sigma =\sigma (X_{t})$ , the Langevin equation in Itô form may in general differ from that in Stratonovich form, in which case the noise term is called multiplicative (i.e., the noise $dW_{t}$ is multiplied by a function of $X_{t}$ that is $\sigma (X_{t})$ ).
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] where $[X,Y]_{T}^{c}$ is the continuous part of the covariation.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] The Stratonovich integral lacks the important property of the Itô integral, which does not "look into the future".
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] In many real-world applications, such as modelling stock prices, one only has information about past events, and hence the Itô interpretation is more natural.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] In financial mathematics the Itô interpretation is usually used.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] In physics, however, stochastic integrals occur as the solutions of Langevin equations.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] A Langevin equation is a coarse-grained version of a more microscopic model (Risken 1996); depending on the problem in consideration, Stratonovich or Itô interpretation or even more exotic interpretations such as the isothermal interpretation, are appropriate.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] The Stratonovich interpretation is the most frequently used interpretation within the physical sciences.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] The Wong–Zakai theorem states that physical systems with non-white noise spectrum characterized by a finite noise correlation time $\tau$ can be approximated by a Langevin equations with white noise in Stratonovich interpretation in the limit where $\tau$ tends to zero.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] Because the Stratonovich calculus satisfies the ordinary chain rule, stochastic differential equations (SDEs) in the Stratonovich sense are more straightforward to define on differentiable manifolds, rather than just on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] The tricky chain rule of the Itô calculus makes it a more awkward choice for manifolds.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] In the supersymmetric theory of SDEs, one considers the evolution operator obtained by averaging the pullback induced on the exterior algebra of the phase space by the stochastic flow determined by an SDE.
[src:ito-stratonovich/stratonovich-integral] In this context, it is then natural to use the Stratonovich interpretation of SDEs.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] In mathematics, the **Wiener process** (or **Brownian motion**, due to its historical connection with the physical process of the same name) is a real-valued continuous-time stochastic process named after Norbert Wiener.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] It is one of the best known Lévy processes (càdlàg stochastic processes with stationary independent increments).
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] It occurs frequently in pure and applied mathematics, economics, quantitative finance, evolutionary biology, and physics.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The Wiener process plays an important role in both pure and applied mathematics.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] In pure mathematics, the Wiener process gave rise to the study of continuous time martingales.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] It is a key process in terms of which more complicated stochastic processes can be described.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] As such, it plays a vital role in stochastic calculus, diffusion processes and even potential theory.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] It is the driving process of Schramm–Loewner evolution.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] In applied mathematics, the Wiener process is used to represent the integral of a white noise Gaussian process, and so is useful as a model of noise in electronics engineering (see Brownian noise), instrument errors in filtering theory and disturbances in control theory.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The Wiener process has applications throughout the mathematical sciences.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] In physics, researchers use it to model Brownian motion and other types of diffusion, often through the Fokker–Planck and Langevin equations, which describe how random motion evolves over time.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] It also underpins the rigorous path integral formulation of quantum mechanics: by the Feynman–Kac formula, one can represent solutions to the Schrödinger equation in terms of the Wiener process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] In physical cosmology, it also appears in models of eternal inflation.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The Wiener process is prominent in the mathematical theory of finance as well, in particular the Black–Scholes option pricing model.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] W has independent increments: for every *t* > 0, the future increments ${\textstyle W_{t+u}-W_{t},\,u\geq 0,}$ are independent of the past values *Ws*, *s* < *t*.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] W has Gaussian increments: for all ${\textstyle u,t\geq 0}$ , ${\textstyle W_{t+u}-W_{t}\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,u).}$ That is, a time step u results in an increment that is normally distributed with mean 0 and variance u.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] W has almost surely continuous paths: *Wt* is almost surely continuous in t.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] That the process has independent increments means that if 0 ≤ *s*1 < *t*1 ≤ *s*2 < *t*2 then *W**t*1 − *W**s*1 and *W**t*2 − *W**s*2 are independent random variables, and the similar condition holds for n increments.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Condition 2 can equivalently be formulated: For every *t* > 0 and ${\textstyle u\geq 0}$ , the increment ${\textstyle W_{t+u}-W_{t}}$ is independent of the sigma-algebra ${\textstyle {\mathcal {F}}_{t}^{B}=\sigma (W_{s}:0\leq s\leq t).}$ .
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] An alternative characterisation of the Wiener process is the so-called *Lévy characterisation* that says that the Wiener process is an almost surely continuous martingale with *W*0 = 0 and quadratic variation [*W**t*, *W**t*] = *t* (which means that *W**t*2 − *t* is also a martingale).
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] A third characterisation is that the Wiener process has a spectral representation as a sine series whose coefficients are independent *N*(0, 1) random variables.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] This representation can be obtained using the Karhunen–Loève theorem.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Another characterisation of a Wiener process is the definite integral (from time zero to time t) of a zero mean, unit variance, delta correlated ("white") Gaussian process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The Wiener process can be constructed as the scaling limit of a random walk, or other discrete-time stochastic processes with stationary independent increments.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Unlike the random walk, it is scale invariant, meaning that $\alpha ^{-1}W_{\alpha ^{2}t}$ is a Wiener process for any nonzero constant α.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The **Wiener measure** is the probability law on the space of continuous functions *g*, with *g*(0) = 0, induced by the Wiener process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] An integral based on Wiener measure may be called a **Wiener integral**.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Let ${\textstyle \xi _{1},\xi _{2},\ldots }$ be i.i.d. random variables with mean 0 and variance 1.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] For each n, define a continuous time stochastic process $W_{n}(t)={\frac {1}{\sqrt {n}}}\sum \limits _{1\leq k\leq \lfloor nt\rfloor }\xi _{k},\qquad t\in [0,1].$ This is a random step function.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Increments of *Wn* are independent because the ${\textstyle \xi _{k}}$ are independent.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] For large n, ${\textstyle W_{n}(t)-W_{n}(s)}$ is close to ${\textstyle N(0,t-s)}$ by the central limit theorem.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Donsker's theorem asserts that as ${\textstyle n\to \infty }$ , *Wn* approaches a Wiener process, which mathematically explains the ubiquity of Brownian motion in natural phenomena.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] These results follow immediately from the definition that increments have a normal distribution, centered at zero.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] These results follow from the definition that non-overlapping increments are independent, of which only the property that they are uncorrelated is used.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] A corollary useful for simulation is that we can write, for *t*1 < *t*2: $W_{t_{2}}=W_{t_{1}}+{\sqrt {t_{2}-t_{1}}}\cdot Z$ where Z is an independent standard normal variable.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Wiener (1923) also gave a representation of a Brownian path in terms of a random Fourier series.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The scaled process ${\sqrt {c}}\,W\left({\frac {t}{c}}\right)$ is a Brownian motion on ${\textstyle [0,c]}$ (cf.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] the probability density function of a Half-normal distribution.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] If at time t the Wiener process has a known value ${\textstyle W_{t}}$ , it is possible to calculate the conditional probability distribution of the maximum in interval ${\textstyle [0,t]}$ (cf.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Probability distribution of extreme points of a Wiener stochastic process).
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] For every *c* > 0 the process ${\textstyle V_{t}=(1/{\sqrt {c}})W_{ct}}$ is another Wiener process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The process ${\textstyle V_{t}=tW_{1/t}}$ is another Wiener process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Consider a Wiener process ${\textstyle W(t)}$ , ${\textstyle t\in \mathbb {R} }$ , conditioned so that ${\textstyle \lim _{t\to \pm \infty }tW(t)=0}$ (which holds almost surely) and as usual ${\textstyle W(0)=0}$ .
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Let ${\textstyle W(t)}$ be a two-dimensional Wiener process, regarded as a complex-valued process with ${\textstyle W(0)=0\in \mathbb {C} }$ .
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] About functions *p*(*xa*, *t*) more general than polynomials, see local martingales.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The set of all functions w with these properties is of full Wiener measure.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The dimension doubling theorems say that the Hausdorff dimension of a set under a Brownian motion doubles almost surely.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The image of the Lebesgue measure on [0, *t*] under the map w (the pushforward measure) has a density *L**t*.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Thus, $\int _{0}^{t}f(w(s))\,\mathrm {d} s=\int _{-\infty }^{+\infty }f(x)L_{t}(x)\,\mathrm {d} x$ for a wide class of functions f (namely: all continuous functions; all locally integrable functions; all non-negative measurable functions).
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The density *Lt* is (more exactly, can and will be chosen to be) continuous.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The number *Lt*(*x*) is called the local time at x of w on [0, *t*].
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] It is strictly positive for all x of the interval (*a*, *b*) where *a* and *b* are the least and the greatest value of w on [0, *t*], respectively.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] (For x outside this interval the local time evidently vanishes.) Treated as a function of two variables x and t, the local time is still continuous.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Treated as a function of t (while x is fixed), the local time is a singular function corresponding to a nonatomic measure on the set of zeros of w.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] These continuity properties are fairly non-trivial.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Consider that the local time can also be defined (as the density of the pushforward measure) for a smooth function.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Then, however, the density is discontinuous, unless the given function is monotone.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] In other words, there is a conflict between good behavior of a function and good behavior of its local time.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] In this sense, the continuity of the local time of the Wiener process is another manifestation of non-smoothness of the trajectory.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] In many cases, it is impossible to encode the Wiener process without sampling it first.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] In particular, ${\textstyle T_{s}/6}$ is the mean squared error associated only with the sampling operation (without encoding).
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The stochastic process defined by $X_{t}=\mu t+\sigma W_{t}$ is called a **Wiener process with drift μ** and infinitesimal variance σ2.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] These processes exhaust continuous Lévy processes, which means that they are the only continuous Lévy processes, as a consequence of the Lévy–Khintchine representation.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Two random processes on the time interval [0, 1] appear, roughly speaking, when conditioning the Wiener process to vanish on both ends of [0,1].
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] With no further conditioning, the process takes both positive and negative values on [0, 1] and is called Brownian bridge.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Conditioned also to stay positive on (0, 1), the process is called Brownian excursion.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] In both cases a rigorous treatment involves a limiting procedure, since the formula *P*(*A*|*B*) = *P*(*A* ∩ *B*)/*P*(*B*) does not apply when *P*(*B*) = 0.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] It is a stochastic process which is used to model processes that can never take on negative values, such as the value of stocks.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The stochastic process $X_{t}=e^{-t}W_{e^{2t}}$ is distributed like the Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process with parameters ${\textstyle \theta =1}$ , ${\textstyle \mu =0}$ , and ${\textstyle \sigma ^{2}=2}$ .
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The time of hitting a single point *x* > 0 by the Wiener process is a random variable with the Lévy distribution.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The family of these random variables (indexed by all positive numbers x) is a left-continuous modification of a Lévy process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The right-continuous modification of this process is given by times of first exit from closed intervals [0, *x*].
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The local time *L* = (*Lxt*)*x* ∈ **R**, *t* ≥ 0 of a Brownian motion describes the time that the process spends at the point x.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The behaviour of the local time is characterised by Ray–Knight theorems.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Then the process *Xt* is a continuous martingale.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Its martingale property follows immediately from the definitions, but its continuity is a very special fact – a special case of a general theorem stating that all Brownian martingales are continuous.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] A Brownian martingale is, by definition, a martingale adapted to the Brownian filtration; and the Brownian filtration is, by definition, the filtration generated by the Wiener process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The time-integral of the Wiener process $W^{(-1)}(t):=\int _{0}^{t}W(s)\,ds$ is called **integrated Brownian motion** or **integrated Wiener process**.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] It arises in many applications and can be shown to have the distribution *N*(0, *t*3/3), calculated using the fact that the covariance of the Wiener process is ${\textstyle t\wedge s=\min(t,s)}$ .
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] All these results can be seen as direct consequences of Itô isometry.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The *n*-times-integrated Wiener process is a zero-mean normal variable with variance ${\textstyle {\frac {t}{2n+1}}\left({\frac {t^{n}}{n!}}\right)^{2}}$ .
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] This is given by the Cauchy formula for repeated integration.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Every continuous martingale (starting at the origin) is a time changed Wiener process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] In general, if M is a continuous martingale then ${\textstyle M_{t}-M_{0}=V_{A(t)}}$ where *A*(*t*) is the quadratic variation of M on [0, *t*], and V is a Wiener process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Especially, a nonnegative continuous martingale has a finite limit (as *t* → ∞) almost surely.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] All stated (in this subsection) for martingales holds also for local martingales.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] A wide class of continuous semimartingales (especially, of diffusion processes) is related to the Wiener process via a combination of time change and change of measure.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Using this fact, the qualitative properties stated above for the Wiener process can be generalized to a wide class of continuous semimartingales.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The complex-valued Wiener process may be defined as a complex-valued random process of the form ${\textstyle Z_{t}=X_{t}+iY_{t}}$ where ${\textstyle X_{t}}$ and ${\textstyle Y_{t}}$ are independent Wiener processes (real-valued).
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] In other words, it is the 2-dimensional Wiener process, where we identify ${\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{2}}$ with ${\textstyle \mathbb {C} }$ .
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Brownian scaling, time reversal, time inversion: the same as in the real-valued case.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] Rotation invariance: for every complex number ${\textstyle c}$ such that ${\textstyle |c|=1}$ the process ${\textstyle c\cdot Z_{t}}$ is another complex-valued Wiener process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] If ${\textstyle f}$ is an entire function then the process ${\textstyle f(Z_{t})-f(0)}$ is a time-changed complex-valued Wiener process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] In contrast to the real-valued case, a complex-valued martingale is generally not a time-changed complex-valued Wiener process.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] For example, the martingale ${\textstyle 2X_{t}+iY_{t}}$ is not (here ${\textstyle X_{t}}$ and ${\textstyle Y_{t}}$ are independent Wiener processes, as before).
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The Brownian sheet is a multiparamateric generalization.
[src:ito-stratonovich/wiener-process] The definition varies from authors, some define the Brownian sheet to have specifically a two-dimensional time parameter ${\textstyle t}$ while others define it for general dimensions.
